SkylineAvenue 2025-02-18 12:15 AM
the better you get the source, the better, as with everything in music
12:18 AM
ofc you can spend a lot of time in cleanup and be stuck polishing turds as the saying goes, which in many cases can def improve things but it ll be just better and less headache overall getting it right at the source. better in that case depends on a lot of things, but the generic stuff ofc is no clipping, use popfilters and keep proper distance from the mic, record in a dampened sounding environment if possible
12:20 AM
then what i usually go for when doing proper takes, if you think you got it, do a few more takes. better a few too many then 1 short. also watch stuff like pronunciation or where you emphasize words or just delivery style overall, try different things on certain takes so you can pick and choose which sounds best later, go ham
saucy_boii 2025-02-18 12:29 AM
what does a proper distance from the mic look like?
SkylineAvenue 2025-02-18 12:30 AM
at least this is a good rule of thumb (no pun intended) already
12:30 AM
it ll go a long way in keeping plosives at bay and not get very loud asmr style mouth plops and all that from being too close into it
saucy_boii 2025-02-18 12:33 AM
ok I was wayyyyy too close to the mic before then
SkylineAvenue 2025-02-18 12:35 AM
it can depend on type of mic too tho but unless youre on stage trynna scream over a metal band behind you while almost swallowing the mic, a bit of distance will get more desirable results. especially ofc going for a studio recording type thing

Alex (Project AER / maru mori.) 2025-03-08 6:29 PM
Chiming in with some recommendations here because I love amp sims in my experience Guitar Rig is my favourite all-rounder, I use it for EVERYTHING. It can do some really 'real' sounding stuff and some more creative stuff. It's great for ambient / rock / pop stuff esp. Amplitube is cool and probably the most 'authentic' but for me it's a bit slow and clunky, so I don't use it much. The neural DSP plugins are some of my absolute favourites but they're all a bit specialised, so they're worth a look, but just be sure of what sort of style / sound of amp sims you're after Another honourable mention is Softube's Amp Room - their Marshall Bluesbreaker is one of my go-tos for crunchy, vintagey sorta tones
1

Alex (Project AER / maru mori.) 2025-03-09 9:24 PM
I've never used a DI box personally, I've always just gone guitar -> interface and that's worked pretty well for me, used to be super noisy when i had a cheap behringer interface, but since I got my Audient interface it's been really solid. I find for me it comes down more to the power / guitar than anything - I've got a power conditioner into an ADAT interface now so I can be sure there's no ground loops and stuff. Then when it comes to something like a strat / single coil pickups they can just be pretty noisy pickups, I think fender do noiseless single coil pickups? I've heard they're not very good tho
9:25 PM
Honestly I think a decent cable into a decent interface (scarlett / audient etc) with as clean power as you can get, you should be pretty good to go with noise
9:26 PM
